definition.value: A harmala alkaloid in which the harman skeleton is methoxy-substituted at C-7.
A cumic acid that consists of benzoic acid substituted by an isopropyl group at position 4.
A member of the class of ethanolamines that is ethanolamine having a N-hydroxyethyl substituent.
A chloroaniline that consists of two 2-chloroaniline units joined by a methylene bridge.
A docosahexaenoic acid having six cis-double bonds at positions 4, 7, 10, 13, 16 and 19.
A member of the class of coumarins that is coumarin substituted by methoxy groups at positions 5, 6 and 7.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 3,5-dibromo-4-hydroxyphenyl group.
The all-trans-isomer of  phytofluene.
A member of the class of prostaglandins J that is prosta-5,9,12-trien-1-oic acid carrying oxo and hydsroxy substituents at positions 11 and 15 respectively (the 5Z,12E,15S-stereoisomer).
A UDP-amino sugar having 3-O-(3-hydroxytetradecanoyl)-N-acetyl-beta-glucosamine as the sugar component.
An amino monosaccharide that consists of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine substituted at position 6 by a sulfo group.
An S-alkyl-L-cysteine in which the sulfur of the thioether moiety has been oxidised to the corresponding sulfoxide.

An undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl peptide in which the peptide element is L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-meso-2,6-diaminopimeloyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine and in which the muramoyl residue is glucosaminyl-substituted at O-4.
A organochlorine compound comprising acetic acid having two 4-chlorophenyl substituents attached at the 2-position.

A tetrahydropyridine that is 1,2,5,6-tetrahydropyridine with a methyl group at position 1, and a methoxycarbonyl group at position 3. An alkaloid found in the areca nut, it acts as an agonist of muscarinic acetylcholine.
An organochlorine compound that is the hydrate of trichloroacetaldehyde.
A mancude organic heterotricyclic parent that consists of a furan ring flanked by two benzene rings ortho-fused across the 2,3- and 4,5-positions.

A D-gluconate adduct of indefinite composition containing between 30 and 34% of antimony(V), calculated with reference to dried and methanol-free substance. It is used as a treatment for leishmaniasis.
A member of the class of dihydrochalcones that is dihydrochalcone with hydroxy substituents at positions 2' ,4' , and 6' and a formyl substituent at position 3'.
A member of the class of tetrahydropterins that is 2-amino-6-(1,2,3-trihydroxypropyl)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteridin-4-one carrying four additional hydroxy substituents at positions 5, 6, 7 and 8.
A dihydroxyflavanone in which the two hydroxy groups are located at positions 5 and 7. A natural product found in Piper sarmentosum and Cryptocarya chartacea.
A prostaglandin Falpha that is prostaglandin F1alpha bearing a keto substituent at the 6-position.
An optically active form of asparagine having D-configuration.
D-Xylopyranose in which the anomeric configuration is beta.
An monoalkyl phosphate compound having an O-3-(indol-3-yl)propyl substituent.
A complex between iron(III) and three hydroxamic acid groups, used for iron transport.
5,6beta-epoxy-5beta-cholestan-3beta-ol
A quercetin trissulfate having the three sulfo groups placed at the 3-, 4'- and 7-positions.
A 3-oxoacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 6-oxocyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxycyclohexane-1-carboxylic acid.
